PPO Training Walkthrough for Qwen2.5-1.5B

This notebook provides a comprehensive walkthrough of the PPO (Proximal Policy Optimization) training pipeline for fine-tuning the Qwen2.5-1.5B language model with sentiment-based rewards.

Contents:

  1. Model Setup - Understanding the three model instances
  2. Sequence Indexing & Masks - Visualizing prompt/response/padding masks
  3. Reward Tensor Alignment - How rewards map to sequence positions
  4. Learning Curves - Training progress from metrics.jsonl
  5. Base vs Aligned Model - Comparing generation before/after training

1. Model Architecture Overview

The PPO training setup requires three model instances:

SetupQwenModel (base: loads weights, creates tokenizer/optimizer)
 QwenModel (adds generation logic with/without KV cache)
    PolicyQwenModel (trainable, requires_grad=True)
    ReferenceQwenModel (frozen, provides KL baseline)
 QwenModelValueHead (adds linear value head for advantage estimation)
  • PolicyQwenModel: The model being trained. Generates text and its parameters are updated via PPO.
  • ReferenceQwenModel: Frozen copy of the initial model. Used to compute KL divergence penalty to prevent the policy from drifting too far.
  • QwenModelValueHead: Predicts state values V(s) for computing advantages in GAE.

2. Understanding Sequence Indexing & Masks: The Action Perspective

A critical aspect of PPO for language models is understanding that masks represent actions, not token membership.

The Key Insight: Actions, Not Tokens

In autoregressive language modeling, each position represents an action (choosing the next token based on the current context). The mask at position i tells us what type of token was generated by the action at position i.

Tokens:      [I] [think] [the] [movie] [was] [great] [!] [<EOS>] [<PAD>]
Positions:    0     1      2      3      4      5     6     7       8

When we compute masks (shifted by 1 to align with log probabilities):

Position i:     0      1      2      3      4      5      6      7
Input token:   [I]  [think] [the] [movie] [was] [great]  [!]  [<EOS>]
                                                         
Generated:   [think] [the] [movie] [was] [great]  [!]  [<EOS>] [???]

Why "was" has response_mask=1

For the prompt "I think the movie was":

  • Position 4 corresponds to inputting "was" generating "great" (first response token)
  • "was" has response_mask=1 not because "was" is part of the response, but because inputting "was" led to generating a response token

Why EOS has response_mask=0

  • The EOS token at position 7 is the last generated token
  • Position 7 would mean: input EOS generate next token
  • But EOS terminates generation, so no response token was generated
  • Therefore, EOS has response_mask=0 even though it IS part of the response

Visual Summary

"I think the movie was"  "great ! <EOS>"

Mask semantics (at position i):

 prompt_mask[i]=1    inputting token[i] generated a PROMPT token    
 response_mask[i]=1  inputting token[i] generated a RESPONSE token  
 padding_mask[i]=1   position i is padding (no real token)

Let's visualize this with real data.

def visualize_masks(response_props, outputs, sample_idx=0, max_tokens=50):
    """
    Create a heatmap visualization of the different masks for a single sample.
    """
    prompt_mask = response_props['prompt_mask'][sample_idx].numpy()[:max_tokens]
    response_mask = response_props['response_mask'][sample_idx].numpy()[:max_tokens]
    padding_mask = response_props['padding_mask'][sample_idx].numpy()[:max_tokens]
    
    # Stack masks for visualization
    mask_matrix = np.stack([
        prompt_mask.astype(float),
        response_mask.astype(float),
        padding_mask.astype(float),
    ])
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(16, 3))
    
    # Create heatmap
    sns.heatmap(
        mask_matrix,
        ax=ax,
        cmap='RdYlGn',
        cbar_kws={'label': 'Mask Value'},
        yticklabels=['Prompt Mask', 'Response Mask', 'Padding Mask'],
        xticklabels=range(max_tokens),
        linewidths=0.5,
        linecolor='gray',
    )
    
    # Add token labels on top
    tokens = response_props['padded_generated_ids'][sample_idx].tolist()[:max_tokens+1]
    token_strs = [base_model.tokenizer.decode([t]) for t in tokens]
    
    ax.set_xlabel('Position (shifted by 1 from token position)')
    ax.set_title(f'Sample {sample_idx}: Mask Visualization\n'
                 f'Input: "{outputs[sample_idx]["input_text"]}" | '
                 f'Response: "{outputs[sample_idx]["response_text"][:40]}..."')
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    return fig

# Visualize masks for first sample
fig = visualize_masks(response_props, outputs, sample_idx=0)
plt.show()

def visualize_action_perspective(response_props, outputs, sample_idx=0, max_display=20):
    """
    Visualize the INPUT  OUTPUT relationship to clarify mask semantics.
    Shows that masks indicate what TYPE of token was GENERATED by each action.
    """
    # Get tokens
    all_tokens = response_props['padded_generated_ids'][sample_idx].tolist()
    input_len = outputs[sample_idx]['input_length']
    response_len = outputs[sample_idx]['generated_response_length']
    total_len = input_len + response_len
    
    # Limit display to keep it readable
    display_len = min(total_len + 2, max_display)
    
    # Decode tokens
    token_strs = [base_model.tokenizer.decode([t]).replace('\n', '').strip() or '' 
                  for t in all_tokens[:display_len + 1]]
    
    # Get masks (these are shifted by 1)
    prompt_mask = response_props['prompt_mask'][sample_idx].numpy()
    response_mask = response_props['response_mask'][sample_idx].numpy()
    padding_mask = response_props['padding_mask'][sample_idx].numpy()
    
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(18, 14))
    
    # === Panel 1: Input  Output Flow (top) ===
    ax1 = fig.add_axes([0.05, 0.55, 0.9, 0.40])  # [left, bottom, width, height]
    ax1.set_xlim(-1.5, display_len + 0.5)
    ax1.set_ylim(-1, 3.5)
    
    # Title
    ax1.set_title(f'Action Perspective: Input Token  Generated Token\n'
                  f'Prompt: "{outputs[sample_idx]["input_text"]}"  '
                  f'Response: "{outputs[sample_idx]["response_text"][:35]}..."', 
                  fontsize=12, fontweight='bold', pad=10)
    
    # Draw input tokens (top row) and output tokens (bottom row) with arrows
    for i in range(display_len):
        # Determine input token color based on its TYPE
        if i < input_len:
            in_color = 'steelblue'
        elif i < total_len:
            in_color = 'seagreen' 
        else:
            in_color = 'lightgray'
        
        # Input token box (top)
        rect = plt.Rectangle((i - 0.4, 2.4), 0.8, 0.7, 
                              facecolor=in_color, edgecolor='black', linewidth=1.5)
        ax1.add_patch(rect)
        ax1.text(i, 2.75, token_strs[i][:7], ha='center', va='center', 
                fontsize=9, fontweight='bold', color='white' if in_color != 'lightgray' else 'black')
        ax1.text(i, 2.2, f'[{i}]', ha='center', va='center', fontsize=7, color='gray')
        
        # Arrow from input to output
        ax1.annotate('', xy=(i, 1.4), xytext=(i, 2.3),
                    arrowprops=dict(arrowstyle='->', color='#555555', lw=2))
        
        # Output token (what was GENERATED by this action) - bottom row
        output_idx = i + 1
        if output_idx < len(token_strs):
            # Color based on what TYPE of token was generated (this determines the mask!)
            if i < input_len - 1:  # Generated a prompt token
                out_color = 'steelblue'
                mask_type = 'P'
            elif i < total_len - 1:  # Generated a response token  
                out_color = 'seagreen'
                mask_type = 'R'
            else:
                out_color = 'lightgray'
                mask_type = '-'
            
            rect = plt.Rectangle((i - 0.4, 0.6), 0.8, 0.7, 
                                  facecolor=out_color, edgecolor='black', linewidth=1.5, alpha=0.8)
            ax1.add_patch(rect)
            ax1.text(i, 0.95, token_strs[output_idx][:7], ha='center', va='center', 
                    fontsize=9, fontweight='bold', color='white' if out_color != 'lightgray' else 'black')
            
            # Mask indicator below
            mask_color = 'darkgreen' if mask_type == 'R' else ('darkblue' if mask_type == 'P' else 'gray')
            ax1.text(i, 0.25, f'mask={mask_type}', ha='center', va='center', 
                    fontsize=7, color=mask_color, fontweight='bold')
    
    # Labels on the left
    ax1.text(-1.2, 2.75, 'INPUT\ntoken[i]', ha='center', va='center', fontsize=10, fontweight='bold')
    ax1.text(-1.2, 0.95, 'OUTPUT\ntoken[i+1]', ha='center', va='center', fontsize=10, fontweight='bold')
    ax1.text(-1.2, 0.25, 'MASK\nat pos i', ha='center', va='center', fontsize=8, fontweight='bold', color='gray')
    
    ax1.axis('off')
    
    # === Panel 2: Legend and Key Insight (middle) ===
    ax2 = fig.add_axes([0.05, 0.38, 0.9, 0.12])
    ax2.set_xlim(0, 10)
    ax2.set_ylim(0, 2)
    
    # Legend boxes
    legend_items = [
        (0.5, 'steelblue', 'P = prompt_mask=1', '(action generated a PROMPT token)'),
        (3.5, 'seagreen', 'R = response_mask=1', '(action generated a RESPONSE token)'),
        (7.0, 'lightgray', '- = padding/no action', '(no token generated)'),
    ]
    
    for x, color, label1, label2 in legend_items:
        rect = plt.Rectangle((x, 0.8), 0.4, 0.8, facecolor=color, edgecolor='black', linewidth=1)
        ax2.add_patch(rect)
        ax2.text(x + 0.6, 1.2, label1, ha='left', va='center', fontsize=10, fontweight='bold')
        ax2.text(x + 0.6, 0.7, label2, ha='left', va='center', fontsize=9, color='gray')
    
    ax2.axis('off')
    
    # === Panel 3: Key Examples with Explanations (bottom) ===
    ax3 = fig.add_axes([0.05, 0.02, 0.9, 0.32])
    ax3.set_xlim(0, 10)
    ax3.set_ylim(0, 4)
    
    # Boundary position explanation (left side)
    boundary_pos = input_len - 1
    ax3.add_patch(plt.Rectangle((0.3, 2.2), 4.2, 1.6, facecolor='#ffffcc', 
                                  edgecolor='#cc9900', linewidth=2, alpha=0.9))
    ax3.text(2.4, 3.5, f'WHY "{token_strs[boundary_pos]}" HAS response_mask=1', 
             ha='center', va='center', fontsize=11, fontweight='bold', color='#806600')
    ax3.text(2.4, 2.95, f'Position {boundary_pos}: token "{token_strs[boundary_pos]}" is the LAST prompt token', 
             ha='center', va='center', fontsize=9)
    ax3.text(2.4, 2.55, f'When we INPUT "{token_strs[boundary_pos]}", we GENERATE "{token_strs[boundary_pos+1]}" (first response)', 
             ha='center', va='center', fontsize=9, fontweight='bold', color='darkgreen')
    
    # EOS explanation (right side)
    eos_pos = min(total_len - 1, display_len - 1)
    ax3.add_patch(plt.Rectangle((5.3, 2.2), 4.4, 1.6, facecolor='#ffe6cc', 
                                  edgecolor='#cc6600', linewidth=2, alpha=0.9))
    ax3.text(7.5, 3.5, 'WHY <EOS> HAS response_mask=0', 
             ha='center', va='center', fontsize=11, fontweight='bold', color='#804000')
    ax3.text(7.5, 2.95, f'Position {eos_pos}: <EOS> is the LAST generated token', 
             ha='center', va='center', fontsize=9)
    ax3.text(7.5, 2.55, 'When we INPUT <EOS>, generation STOPS (no token generated)', 
             ha='center', va='center', fontsize=9, fontweight='bold', color='#cc3300')
    
    # Key insight box at bottom
    ax3.add_patch(plt.Rectangle((0.3, 0.3), 9.4, 1.5, facecolor='#e6f3ff', 
                                  edgecolor='#0066cc', linewidth=2))
    ax3.text(5, 1.45, 'KEY INSIGHT', ha='center', va='center', 
             fontsize=12, fontweight='bold', color='#004080')
    ax3.text(5, 0.95, 'Masks are about ACTIONS (what was generated), NOT about token membership!', 
             ha='center', va='center', fontsize=11, color='#004080')
    ax3.text(5, 0.55, 'mask[i] = 1 means: "inputting token[i] caused generation of a [prompt/response] token"', 
             ha='center', va='center', fontsize=10, style='italic', color='#336699')
    
    ax3.axis('off')
    
    plt.suptitle('', fontsize=1)  # Clear any default suptitle
    return fig

3. Reward Tensor Alignment

In PPO, rewards are sparse - we only get a reward at the end of the response. The reward is placed at position response_length - 2 (accounting for the shift).

Let's visualize how rewards align with the sequence positions.

def collate_rewards_tensor(rewards_list, response_id_lengths, max_len):
    """
    Collate rewards into a tensor aligned with generated sequences.
    Mirrors PPOTrainer.collate_rewards_tensor
    """
    batch_size = len(rewards_list)
    rewards_tensor = torch.zeros((batch_size, max_len))
    
    for i in range(batch_size):
        response_length = response_id_lengths[i]
        # Place reward at last response action position
        reward_position = max(0, response_length - 2)
        rewards_tensor[i, reward_position] = rewards_list[i]['reward']
    
    return rewards_tensor

# Create reward tensor
reward_values = [r['reward'] for r in rewards]
response_id_lengths = response_props['response_id_lengths']
max_len = response_props['response_mask'].shape[1]

rewards_tensor = collate_rewards_tensor(rewards, response_id_lengths, max_len)
print(f"Rewards tensor shape: {rewards_tensor.shape}")

def visualize_rewards_alignment(response_props, rewards_tensor, outputs, max_tokens=50):
    """
    Visualize how rewards align with response masks.
    """
    n_samples = len(outputs)
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(n_samples, 1, figsize=(16, 3 * n_samples))
    
    if n_samples == 1:
        axes = [axes]
    
    for idx, ax in enumerate(axes):
        response_mask = response_props['response_mask'][idx].numpy()[:max_tokens]
        reward_row = rewards_tensor[idx].numpy()[:max_tokens]
        
        # Create visualization matrix
        vis_matrix = np.stack([response_mask.astype(float), reward_row])
        
        # Normalize rewards for visualization
        reward_normalized = reward_row.copy()
        if np.abs(reward_row).max() > 0:
            reward_normalized = reward_row / np.abs(reward_row).max()
        
        vis_matrix[1] = reward_normalized
        
        sns.heatmap(
            vis_matrix,
            ax=ax,
            cmap='RdYlGn',
            center=0,
            yticklabels=['Response Mask', 'Reward (normalized)'],
            cbar_kws={'label': 'Value'},
            linewidths=0.5,
        )
        
        # Mark reward position
        reward_pos = np.argmax(np.abs(reward_row))
        reward_val = reward_row[reward_pos]
        
        ax.set_title(
            f'Sample {idx}: Reward={reward_val:+.2f} at position {reward_pos}\n'
            f'"{outputs[idx]["input_text"]}"  "{outputs[idx]["response_text"][:30]}..."'
        )
        ax.set_xlabel('Position')
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    return fig

fig = visualize_rewards_alignment(response_props, rewards_tensor, outputs)
plt.show()

def visualize_complete_ppo_data(response_props, rewards_tensor, outputs, sample_idx=0, max_tokens=50):
    """
    Complete visualization showing tokens, masks, logprobs, and rewards.
    """
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(4, 1, figsize=(18, 10), gridspec_kw={'height_ratios': [1, 1, 2, 1]})
    
    # Get data for sample
    tokens = response_props['padded_generated_ids'][sample_idx].tolist()[:max_tokens]
    token_strs = [base_model.tokenizer.decode([t]).replace('\n', '\\n')[:6] for t in tokens]
    
    prompt_mask = response_props['prompt_mask'][sample_idx].numpy()[:max_tokens]
    response_mask = response_props['response_mask'][sample_idx].numpy()[:max_tokens]
    padding_mask = response_props['padding_mask'][sample_idx].numpy()[:max_tokens]
    logprobs = response_props['logprobs'][sample_idx].numpy()[:max_tokens]
    reward_row = rewards_tensor[sample_idx].numpy()[:max_tokens]
    
    # 1. Token display
    ax = axes[0]
    ax.set_xlim(-0.5, max_tokens - 0.5)
    ax.set_ylim(0, 1)
    for i, tok in enumerate(token_strs):
        color = 'steelblue' if prompt_mask[i] else ('seagreen' if response_mask[i] else 'lightgray')
        ax.text(i, 0.5, tok, ha='center', va='center', fontsize=8, 
                bbox=dict(boxstyle='round', facecolor=color, alpha=0.7))
    ax.set_title(f'Tokens (blue=prompt, green=response, gray=padding)')
    ax.axis('off')
    
    # 2. Masks heatmap
    ax = axes[1]
    mask_matrix = np.stack([prompt_mask, response_mask, padding_mask])
    sns.heatmap(mask_matrix, ax=ax, cmap='Blues', cbar=False,
                yticklabels=['Prompt', 'Response', 'Padding'],
                xticklabels=False, linewidths=0.5)
    ax.set_title('Masks')
    
    # 3. Log probabilities
    ax = axes[2]
    colors = ['steelblue' if prompt_mask[i] else ('seagreen' if response_mask[i] else 'lightgray') 
              for i in range(len(logprobs))]
    bars = ax.bar(range(len(logprobs)), logprobs, color=colors, edgecolor='black', linewidth=0.5)
    ax.set_ylabel('Log Probability')
    ax.set_title('Token Log Probabilities (colored by mask type)')
    ax.axhline(y=0, color='black', linestyle='-', linewidth=0.5)
    ax.set_xlim(-0.5, max_tokens - 0.5)
    
    # 4. Reward placement
    ax = axes[3]
    reward_colors = ['green' if r > 0 else ('red' if r < 0 else 'gray') for r in reward_row]
    ax.bar(range(len(reward_row)), reward_row, color=reward_colors, edgecolor='black')
    ax.set_xlabel('Position')
    ax.set_ylabel('Reward')
    ax.set_title('Reward Tensor (sparse - only at end of response)')
    ax.set_xlim(-0.5, max_tokens - 0.5)
    ax.axhline(y=0, color='black', linestyle='-', linewidth=0.5)
    
    plt.suptitle(
        f'Complete PPO Data View - Sample {sample_idx}\n'
        f'Input: "{outputs[sample_idx]["input_text"]}" | '
        f'Response: "{outputs[sample_idx]["response_text"][:40]}..."',
        fontsize=12, y=1.02
    )
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    return fig

4. Learning Curves

Now let's analyze the training progress using the metrics saved during PPO training. We'll examine:

Primary Metrics:

  • mean_reward: Average reward per batch (should increase for positive sentiment)
  • eos_rate: Fraction of generations that produced an EOS token (model learned to terminate)

Loss Components (separate plots):

  • policy_loss: PPO clipped surrogate objective
  • value_loss: MSE between predicted and actual returns

Training Stability (separate plots):

  • approx_kl: KL divergence from reference model (should stay bounded by max_kl=0.05)
  • clip_fraction: Fraction of policy updates that hit the clipping boundary (=0.2)

def plot_learning_curves(df):
    """
    Plot the main learning curves from PPO training.
    """
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(14, 10))
    
    # 1. Mean Reward
    ax = axes[0, 0]
    ax.plot(df['step'], df['mean_reward'], 'b-', alpha=0.3, label='Raw')
    ax.plot(df['step'], df['mean_reward'].rolling(window=20).mean(), 'b-', linewidth=2, label='Smoothed (20)')
    ax.fill_between(df['step'], 
                    df['mean_reward'] - df['std_reward'],
                    df['mean_reward'] + df['std_reward'],
                    alpha=0.2, color='blue')
    ax.axhline(y=0, color='gray', linestyle='--', linewidth=1)
    ax.set_xlabel('Training Step')
    ax.set_ylabel('Mean Reward')
    ax.set_title('Mean Reward Over Training')
    ax.legend()
    ax.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
    
    # 2. EOS Rate
    ax = axes[0, 1]
    ax.plot(df['step'], df['eos_rate'], 'g-', alpha=0.3, label='Raw')
    ax.plot(df['step'], df['eos_rate'].rolling(window=20).mean(), 'g-', linewidth=2, label='Smoothed (20)')
    ax.axhline(y=1.0, color='gray', linestyle='--', linewidth=1, label='Target (100%)')
    ax.set_xlabel('Training Step')
    ax.set_ylabel('EOS Rate')
    ax.set_title('EOS Token Rate (Generation Completion)')
    ax.set_ylim(-0.05, 1.05)
    ax.legend()
    ax.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
    
    # 3. Response Length
    ax = axes[1, 0]
    ax.plot(df['step'], df['mean_response_length'], 'purple', alpha=0.3, label='Raw')
    ax.plot(df['step'], df['mean_response_length'].rolling(window=20).mean(), 'purple', linewidth=2, label='Smoothed (20)')
    ax.set_xlabel('Training Step')
    ax.set_ylabel('Mean Response Length')
    ax.set_title('Response Length Over Training')
    ax.legend()
    ax.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
    
    # 4. Entropy
    ax = axes[1, 1]
    ax.plot(df['step'], df['entropy'], 'orange', alpha=0.3, label='Raw')
    ax.plot(df['step'], df['entropy'].rolling(window=20).mean(), 'orange', linewidth=2, label='Smoothed (20)')
    ax.set_xlabel('Training Step')
    ax.set_ylabel('Entropy')
    ax.set_title('Policy Entropy Over Training')
    ax.legend()
    ax.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    return fig

fig = plot_learning_curves(df)
plt.show()

def plot_losses_separate(df):
    """
    Plot policy loss and value loss in separate subplots for clarity.
    """
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(14, 5))
    
    # Policy Loss
    ax = axes[0]
    ax.plot(df['step'], df['policy_loss'], 'r-', alpha=0.2, label='Raw')
    ax.plot(df['step'], df['policy_loss'].rolling(window=20).mean(), 'r-', linewidth=2, label='Smoothed (20)')
    ax.fill_between(df['step'],
                    df['policy_loss'].rolling(window=20).quantile(0.25),
                    df['policy_loss'].rolling(window=20).quantile(0.75),
                    alpha=0.2, color='red', label='IQR')
    ax.axhline(y=0, color='gray', linestyle='--', linewidth=1)
    ax.set_xlabel('Training Step')
    ax.set_ylabel('Policy Loss')
    ax.set_title('Policy Loss Over Training\n(PPO clipped surrogate objective)')
    ax.legend()
    ax.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
    
    # Value Loss
    ax = axes[1]
    ax.plot(df['step'], df['value_loss'], 'purple', alpha=0.2, label='Raw')
    ax.plot(df['step'], df['value_loss'].rolling(window=20).mean(), 'purple', linewidth=2, label='Smoothed (20)')
    ax.fill_between(df['step'],
                    df['value_loss'].rolling(window=20).quantile(0.25),
                    df['value_loss'].rolling(window=20).quantile(0.75),
                    alpha=0.2, color='purple', label='IQR')
    ax.set_xlabel('Training Step')
    ax.set_ylabel('Value Loss')
    ax.set_title('Value Loss Over Training\n(MSE between predicted and actual returns)')
    ax.legend()
    ax.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    return fig

fig = plot_losses_separate(df)
plt.show()

def plot_kl_and_clipping_separate(df):
    """
    Plot KL divergence and clip fraction in separate subplots.
    """
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(14, 5))
    
    # Approximate KL Divergence
    ax = axes[0]
    ax.plot(df['step'], df['approx_kl'], 'orange', alpha=0.2, label='Raw')
    ax.plot(df['step'], df['approx_kl'].rolling(window=20).mean(), 'orange', linewidth=2, label='Smoothed (20)')
    ax.axhline(y=0.05, color='red', linestyle='--', linewidth=1.5, label='max_kl threshold (0.05)')
    ax.axhline(y=0.015, color='green', linestyle=':', linewidth=1.5, label='target_kl (0.015)')
    ax.set_xlabel('Training Step')
    ax.set_ylabel('Approximate KL')
    ax.set_title('KL Divergence from Reference Model\n(measures policy drift)')
    ax.legend()
    ax.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
    ax.set_ylim(bottom=0)
    
    # Clip Fraction
    ax = axes[1]
    ax.plot(df['step'], df['clip_fraction'], 'cyan', alpha=0.2, label='Raw')
    ax.plot(df['step'], df['clip_fraction'].rolling(window=20).mean(), 'cyan', linewidth=2, label='Smoothed (20)')
    ax.axhline(y=0.2, color='red', linestyle='--', linewidth=1.5, label='High clipping indicator')
    ax.set_xlabel('Training Step')
    ax.set_ylabel('Clip Fraction')
    ax.set_title('PPO Clip Fraction\n(fraction of updates hitting clip boundary)')
    ax.legend()
    ax.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
    ax.set_ylim(0, 0.5)
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    return fig

fig = plot_kl_and_clipping_separate(df)
plt.show()

def plot_reward_and_eos_combined(df):
    """
    Combined plot showing the relationship between EOS rate and reward.
    """
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(14, 6))
    
    # Create twin axis
    ax2 = ax.twinx()
    
    # Plot reward
    line1, = ax.plot(df['step'], df['mean_reward'].rolling(window=20).mean(), 
                     'b-', linewidth=2.5, label='Mean Reward')
    ax.fill_between(df['step'],
                    (df['mean_reward'] - df['std_reward']).rolling(window=20).mean(),
                    (df['mean_reward'] + df['std_reward']).rolling(window=20).mean(),
                    alpha=0.2, color='blue')
    
    # Plot EOS rate
    line2, = ax2.plot(df['step'], df['eos_rate'].rolling(window=20).mean(),
                      'g-', linewidth=2.5, label='EOS Rate')
    
    # Styling
    ax.set_xlabel('Training Step', fontsize=12)
    ax.set_ylabel('Mean Reward', color='blue', fontsize=12)
    ax2.set_ylabel('EOS Rate', color='green', fontsize=12)
    
    ax.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor='blue')
    ax2.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor='green')
    
    # Reference lines
    ax.axhline(y=0, color='blue', linestyle='--', alpha=0.3)
    ax.axhline(y=-10, color='red', linestyle=':', alpha=0.5, label='No EOS penalty (-10)')
    ax2.axhline(y=1.0, color='green', linestyle='--', alpha=0.3)
    
    # Combined legend
    lines = [line1, line2]
    labels = [l.get_label() for l in lines]
    ax.legend(lines, labels, loc='center right', fontsize=11)
    
    ax.set_title('PPO Training Progress: Reward and EOS Rate', fontsize=14)
    ax.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
    
    # Add annotations
    ax.annotate('Model learns to\ngenerate EOS', 
                xy=(df[df['eos_rate'] > 0.5]['step'].iloc[0] if (df['eos_rate'] > 0.5).any() else 1000, 0),
                xytext=(1500, -5),
                fontsize=10,
                arrowprops=dict(arrowstyle='->', color='gray'),
                bbox=dict(boxstyle='round', facecolor='wheat', alpha=0.5))
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    return fig

fig = plot_reward_and_eos_combined(df)

def compare_models(base_model, aligned_model, prompts, gen_config, rewarder):
    """
    Compare generations from base and aligned models.
    """
    results = []
    
    for prompt in prompts:
        # Generate from base model
        base_output = base_model.generate(prompt, config=gen_config)
        base_text = base_output['input_text'] + base_output['response_text']
        base_reward = rewarder.get_reward(base_text)
        if base_output['end_token_found'] is False:
            base_reward['reward'] -= 10.0  # EOS penalty
        
        # Generate from aligned model
        aligned_output = aligned_model.generate(prompt, config=gen_config)
        aligned_text = aligned_output['input_text'] + aligned_output['response_text']
        aligned_reward = rewarder.get_reward(aligned_text)
        if aligned_output['end_token_found'] is False:
            aligned_reward['reward'] -= 10.0  # EOS penalty
        
        results.append({
            'prompt': prompt,
            'base_response': base_output['response_text'],
            'base_reward': base_reward['reward'],
            'base_sentiment': base_reward['label'],
            'base_eos': base_output['end_token_found'],
            'aligned_response': aligned_output['response_text'],
            'aligned_reward': aligned_reward['reward'],
            'aligned_sentiment': aligned_reward['label'],
            'aligned_eos': aligned_output['end_token_found'],
        })
    
    return results

print("Generating comparisons...")
comparison_results = compare_models(base_model, aligned_model, test_prompts, gen_config, rewarder)

def plot_comparison_summary(results):
    """
    Visualize the comparison between base and aligned models.
    """
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(15, 5))
    
    prompts_short = [r['prompt'][:15] + '...' for r in results]
    base_rewards = [r['base_reward'] for r in results]
    aligned_rewards = [r['aligned_reward'] for r in results]
    
    x = np.arange(len(prompts_short))
    width = 0.35
    
    # 1. Reward comparison
    ax = axes[0]
    bars1 = ax.bar(x - width/2, base_rewards, width, label='Base Model', color='steelblue', alpha=0.8)
    bars2 = ax.bar(x + width/2, aligned_rewards, width, label='Aligned Model', color='seagreen', alpha=0.8)
    ax.set_ylabel('Reward')
    ax.set_title('Reward Comparison')
    ax.set_xticks(x)
    ax.set_xticklabels(prompts_short, rotation=45, ha='right')
    ax.legend()
    ax.axhline(y=0, color='gray', linestyle='--', linewidth=1)
    ax.grid(True, alpha=0.3, axis='y')
    
    # 2. Sentiment distribution
    ax = axes[1]
    sentiment_counts = {
        'Base': {'positive': 0, 'neutral': 0, 'negative': 0},
        'Aligned': {'positive': 0, 'neutral': 0, 'negative': 0}
    }
    for r in results:
        sentiment_counts['Base'][r['base_sentiment']] += 1
        sentiment_counts['Aligned'][r['aligned_sentiment']] += 1
    
    sentiments = ['positive', 'neutral', 'negative']
    x_sent = np.arange(len(sentiments))
    base_counts = [sentiment_counts['Base'][s] for s in sentiments]
    aligned_counts = [sentiment_counts['Aligned'][s] for s in sentiments]
    
    ax.bar(x_sent - width/2, base_counts, width, label='Base', color='steelblue', alpha=0.8)
    ax.bar(x_sent + width/2, aligned_counts, width, label='Aligned', color='seagreen', alpha=0.8)
    ax.set_ylabel('Count')
    ax.set_title('Sentiment Distribution')
    ax.set_xticks(x_sent)
    ax.set_xticklabels(['Positive', 'Neutral', 'Negative'])
    ax.legend()
    ax.grid(True, alpha=0.3, axis='y')
    
    # 3. Average metrics
    ax = axes[2]
    metrics = ['Avg Reward', 'EOS Rate']
    base_metrics = [
        np.mean(base_rewards),
        np.mean([r['base_eos'] for r in results])
    ]
    aligned_metrics = [
        np.mean(aligned_rewards),
        np.mean([r['aligned_eos'] for r in results])
    ]
    
    # Normalize for visualization
    base_normalized = [base_metrics[0] / 10, base_metrics[1]]  # Normalize reward to ~1 scale
    aligned_normalized = [aligned_metrics[0] / 10, aligned_metrics[1]]
    
    x_met = np.arange(len(metrics))
    ax.bar(x_met - width/2, base_normalized, width, label='Base', color='steelblue', alpha=0.8)
    ax.bar(x_met + width/2, aligned_normalized, width, label='Aligned', color='seagreen', alpha=0.8)
    ax.set_ylabel('Value (Reward/10, EOS Rate)')
    ax.set_title('Average Metrics')
    ax.set_xticks(x_met)
    ax.set_xticklabels(metrics)
    ax.legend()
    ax.grid(True, alpha=0.3, axis='y')
    
    # Add text annotations with actual values
    for i, (b, a) in enumerate(zip(base_metrics, aligned_metrics)):
        ax.text(i - width/2, base_normalized[i] + 0.05, f'{b:.2f}', ha='center', fontsize=9)
        ax.text(i + width/2, aligned_normalized[i] + 0.05, f'{a:.2f}', ha='center', fontsize=9)
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    return fig

fig = plot_comparison_summary(comparison_results)

Conclusion

This notebook demonstrated the key concepts in PPO training for language models:

  1. Model Setup: The three-model architecture (Policy, Reference, Value) required for PPO

  2. Action-Based Mask Semantics:

    • Masks indicate what type of token was generated, not token membership
    • response_mask[i]=1 means the action at position i (inputting token[i]) generated a response token
    • The last prompt token (e.g., "was") has response_mask=1 because it triggered the first response token
    • EOS has response_mask=0 because it terminates generation (no token generated after it)

  3. Reward Alignment: Sparse rewards placed at position response_length - 2 (the last response action)

  4. Learning Curves:

    • Mean reward improved from -10 (no EOS penalty) to +9.8 (positive sentiment)
    • EOS rate increased from 0% to 100%
    • Policy and value losses, KL divergence, and clip fractions stayed stable

  5. Model Comparison: The aligned model generates positive sentiment completions and properly terminates with EOS

The PPO training successfully steered the model toward generating positive sentiment text while learning to properly terminate responses.
